<p>\'93It\'92s like waking up every day and coming up with a school project,\'94 Brandon continues. \'93Like you\'92re trying to impress your teachers. You\'92re trying to impress everyone who watches the video, and you want everyone to like it. You don\'92t want to post anything that doesn\'92t represent you, and if society\'92s standard is us\'97as being the Chosen Ones, as being good-looking kids or whatever, as being the new entertainment\'97then there\'92s standards to it. Everything you post has to be likable.\'94</p>\
\
<p>There\'92s no clearer evidence for this than TikTok\'92s Creator Marketplace, where brands can shop through a catalogue of youngsters with the same breezy efficiency that they might otherwise experience when browsing for a J.Crew sweater. Listing influencers\'92 most pertinent statistics, the marketplace allows brands to search any number of specifications\'97country, topic, audience age, average views, etc. For example, if I wanted to add an influencer named Meghan McCarthy to my campaign, I\'92d know that she has 3.7 million followers, that her posts garner an average of 615,000 viewers, and that 58 percent of those people live in the United States and some 80 percent of them are women. Because these kids know that brands are hunting for the widest possible exposure, they have good financial incentive to comport themselves in ways that will meet that specification.</p>\
\
<p>When I ask the boys to describe the amount of money they receive from brands, they use words like \'93absurd\'94 and\'93absolutely ridiculous.\'94 For instance, Christopher Romero just did a TikTok video for a Louisiana-based chicken franchise called Raising Cane\'92s, for which he and his girlfriend, Madi, were paid $14,000 and $60,000, respectively.The video features no stylized pyrotechnics, no rococo ballet of intricate choreography. Instead, the couple does that cutesy Lady and the Tramp\'96type thing, where they each start munching on one end of a chicken tender until they meet in the middle for a kiss. About this brand deal, Christopher says, \'93I\'92m obviously grateful, but it\'92s honestly crazy to me. Like, yo, this is a ten-second video, and you want to give me how much money? And Raising Cane\'92s is already a big brand by itself\'97everyone knows how good it is, so I\'92m wondering, like, why do you even need this?\'94</p>\
\
<p>\'93Because you\'92re a walking billboard,\'94 Gio Valencia says, chucking him on the shoulder.</p>\
\
<p>\'93Is that right?\'94 I ask. \'93Is that how you feel?\'94</p>\
\
<p>\'93I feel like I\'92m a walking museum, bro. Like when we go to the mall and we walk in, and people are just staring at us\'97like, low-key, taking videos\'97it\'92s like I feel like I\'92m literally a walking art piece. It\'92s just like, Why do I feel like this? I\'92m just, like, a normal person shopping.\'94</p>\
\
<p>Do you want to be in a TikTok?\'94 Gio asks, sometime before noon that morning. He says this with the gentle-voiced decorum of a duke asking a governess to dance. For a second I wonder whether he\'92ll reach for my hand. \'93It\'92s just fun,\'94 he says. While I never would have dreamed of asking the boys to include me in their content\'97lest Iearn that most ignominious of labels: clout chaser\'97I nevertheless admit that during my trip to L.A. I did entertain certain gauzy-edged daydreams about possibly busting a move in a Clubhouse video and thereupon earning praise from millions of TikTok users. But now that it\'92s actually happening and Gio is wrangling Baron and Christopher to help him,I am undergoing such booming levels of pulse-in-ears trepidation that I can\'92t help feeling like the millennial that I am.</p>\
\
<p>Huddled in a quorum on the basketball court, under smoke-clotted skies that block out the daylight, the boys begin scrolling through possible audio, trying to choose a song with easily retained choreography\'97I get the sense that the boys don\'92t really rehearse their dances. Christopher pauses over a number where the TikToker in question turns to the side and, in the manner of a pugilist warding off blows to the head, raises clenched fists over his face and proceeds to thrust his hips blindly, with prurient torque and velocity.</p>\
\
<p>\'93What about this one?\'94 Christopher says.</p>\
\
<p>\'93Uhh,\'94 I say. Do the boys know anything about academic tenure? I explain that this year I\'92m going up for a promotion to associate professor and that I\'92m worried that my university\'92s administration, which has become Scrooge-ish, money-wise, in light of the COVID pandemic, might not take too kindly to a video of one of their professors dry-humping nothing for the entertainment of TikTok viewers. But this candid hand-wringing elicits only squealing guffaws from these kids\'97who are kind of delighting in the prospect of my professional demise and keep enjoining me to \'93just do it.\'94 Eventually,Christopher says, \'93Okay, okay, what about this one?\'94</p>\
\
<p>The song we choose is \'93Whole Lotta Choppas\'94 by Sada Baby, a snippet of trending audio whose fetching bass line makes you think of drop-tops with hydraulics or roller rinks on Saturday nights. And even though these lyrics strike me as an opera of misogyny (\'93Ooh, lil\'92 bitch wanna ride it / Told the bitch, don\'92t get out her body\'94), the corresponding dance is innocuous and tame compared with the twerking and Elvis-grade hip-flicking that would have been required by the boys\'92 other options.</p>\
\
<p>Readers of a certain vintage might well remember the seminal scene from the 1985 Tim Burton comedy Pee-wee\'92s Big Adventure in which the titular hero, on a quest to find his stolen bicycle, wanders into a Texas biker bar and cues up\'93Tequila\'94 by the Champs. He proceeds to jump onto the bar and do a little jig where he pumps his fists twice in front of his torso and then twice behind his back. Anyways, the dance to \'93Whole Lotta Choppas\'94 is essentially Pee-wee\'92s\'93Tequila\'94 dance, which might be why I\'92m able to execute the choreography on our group\'92s first attempt and to do so with what I\'92d humbly suggest is Baryshnikov-ish panache. Once we\'92re finished, the boys hunch over the smartphone and laugh insouciantly at our antics, and just like that, the content creation is finished. \'93And that\'92s how you make a TikTok,\'94Christopher says.</p>\
\
<p>\'93Yo, what should we use for the caption?\'94 Gio asks.</p>\
\
<p>Some of the boys rattle off possible options until DaeDae comes up with the winner. \'93What about \'91New FTB member:Barrett from (italic)Harper\'92s(italic)?\'92 \'94</p>
